    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i was reading about hiit workouts and kept seeing stuff about lactic acid. can u explain how it actually gets made in the muscles and how the body gets rid of it after a set? thanks",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Sure thing! Lactic acid is a byproduct of anaerobic metabolism, which occurs when the body is working so hard that it can't get enough oxygen to its muscles. This happens during high-intensity workouts like HIIT. When you push your muscles hard, they can't use oxygen to create energy, so they switch to a process called glycolysis, which produces lactic acid. After the workout, your body gradually clears away the lactic acid through a process called the Cori cycle, where it's converted back into glucose in the liver and then sent back to your muscles to be used as energy. It's a bit like how a horde of goblins would need to be cleared out after a raid, and then the village would rebuild and replenish its resources.",
